public class CustomersTraining : TrainingContentBase
{
    public CustomersTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customers Overview",
            Slug = "customers-overview",
            Summary = "What the Customers module does, the lifecycle-driven detail tabs, contacts, addresses, credit management, and how customers connect to quotes, orders, jobs, and invoices.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","contacts","addresses","credit"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customers Overview\n\nThe Customers module is your central customer relationship hub. It tracks every customer your shop works with — their contact people, addresses, credit status, estimates, quotes, sales orders, jobs, invoices, and full activity history. Every customer gets a dedicated detail page whose tab set is lifecycle-driven — it adapts to where the customer is in their relationship with your shop — giving you a 360-degree view.\n\n### Customer List Page\n\nThe main `/customers` page shows all customers in a searchable, sortable data table. You can filter by active/inactive status and search by name, company, email, or phone. Click any row to navigate to that customer's detail page. The Add Customer button opens a quick-create dialog with name, company name, email, and phone fields.\n\n### Customer Detail Page — Lifecycle-Driven Tabs\n\nEvery customer detail page lives at `/customers/:id/:tab` and includes a header with the customer name, company, contact info, active/inactive status chip, and an accounting integration badge when synced with an external provider like QuickBooks.\n\n**The tab set is not fixed — it adapts to the customer's lifecycle bucket** (derived from whether the customer is active plus their open-document counts). Overview is always first and Activity is always last; the middle tabs vary:\n- **Active** (active customer with open estimates, quotes, orders, jobs, or invoices): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Estimates, Quotes, Orders, Jobs, Invoices, Pricing, Interactions, Activity (11 tabs)\n- **Prospect** (active but no open business yet): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Estimates, Quotes, Interactions, Activity (7 tabs — Orders, Jobs, Invoices, and Pricing are hidden until there's business)\n- **Archived** (inactive customer): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Invoices, Interactions, Activity (6 tabs — read-only history posture, Invoices kept for any unpaid balances)\n\nTabs whose backing capability is disabled (Contacts, Addresses, Interactions) drop out as well. The sections below describe each tab you may encounter.\n\n#### Stats Bar\n\nBelow the header, a clickable stats bar shows live aggregates:\n- **Open Estimates** — count of non-closed estimates\n- **Open Quotes** — count of active quotes\n- **Open Orders** — count of in-progress sales orders\n- **Active Jobs** — count of jobs currently on the kanban board\n- **Outstanding** — total dollar amount of unpaid invoices\n- **YTD Revenue** — total revenue from this customer in the current year\n\nClicking a stat switches to the corresponding tab for quick drill-down.\n\n#### Overview\n\nShows account details (name, company, email, phone, status, customer-since date), accounting integration info (provider, external ID, reference) when connected, and the Credit Status card.\n\n**Credit Status Card** displays:\n- Risk level chip (Low/Medium/High/OnHold)\n- Credit Hold banner with reason and Release button (when on hold)\n- Credit Limit, Open AR balance, Pending Orders total, Total Exposure, Available Credit, and Utilization percentage\n- Visual utilization bar that turns red when over limit\n- Place Hold button to block new orders with a required reason\n\n#### Contacts\n\nManage contact people for this customer. Each contact is displayed as a card with avatar, name (Last, First format), role, email, phone, and primary contact badge. You can add, edit, and remove contacts. Contact roles come from reference data (database-driven, not hardcoded).\n\n#### Interactions\n\nLog and track customer interactions — calls, emails, meetings, and notes. Each interaction records the type, subject, contact, who logged it, date, duration, and notes. Filter by contact or type. The table shows type (with icon), subject, contact name, logged-by user, date, and duration.\n\n#### Addresses\n\nView all addresses on file. Each address card shows the address type chip (Billing, Shipping, etc.), a Default badge if applicable, and the full address (line 1, line 2, city, state, ZIP, country).\n\n#### Estimates\n\nNon-binding ballpark figures for potential work. Each estimate has a title, description, estimated amount, valid-until date, status (Draft, Sent, Accepted, Declined, Expired), and notes. Estimates can be converted to formal Quotes via the convert button. The table shows title, amount, status, valid-until date, created date, and action buttons (convert to quote, delete).\n\n#### Quotes\n\nBinding, line-itemized price commitments. The table shows quote number, status, total amount, expiration date, and created date. Click a row to open the full quote detail dialog.\n\n#### Orders\n\nSales orders for this customer. The table shows order number, status (color-coded chip), total, requested date, and created date. Click to open the sales order detail dialog.\n\n#### Jobs\n\nAll kanban jobs linked to this customer. The table shows job title, stage (color-coded chip matching the kanban stage color), due date, and created date. Click to open the job detail dialog.\n\n#### Invoices\n\nInvoices issued to this customer. The table shows invoice number, status, total, due date, and created date. Click to open the invoice detail dialog.\n\n#### Pricing\n\nCustomer-specific price lists and quantity-break entries (Active customers only). Lets Office Managers adjust negotiated pricing in-context.\n\n#### Activity\n\nChronological activity timeline showing all changes, comments, and events related to this customer. Uses the shared ActivityTimeline component.\n\n### How Customers Connect to Other Features\n\n**Quote-to-Cash Flow:** Customer → Estimate → Quote → Sales Order → Job → Shipment → Invoice → Payment. Every step in this chain links back to the customer record.\n\n**Jobs:** When a job is created on the kanban board, it can be assigned to a customer. The customer's Jobs tab shows all linked jobs.\n\n**Credit Management:** The credit status card monitors exposure (open AR + pending orders) against the credit limit. When a customer is on credit hold, new orders are blocked until the hold is released.\n\n**Accounting Integration:** When connected to QuickBooks or another accounting provider, the customer record syncs bidirectionally. The provider badge and external IDs appear in the Overview tab.\n\n### When to Use Customers\n\n- When onboarding a new customer for the first time\n- When looking up a customer's full history (orders, jobs, invoices)\n- When checking credit status before accepting a new order\n- When logging a phone call, email, or meeting with a customer contact\n- When managing billing and shipping addresses\n- When creating estimates or converting them to formal quotes","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
