        // ── Customer-Specific Pricing (Article) ──────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer-Specific Pricing",
            Slug = "customers-pricing",
            Summary = "How the Pricing tab works: building negotiated price lists, adding quantity-break entries, inline-editing prices, and bulk-importing entries from CSV.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","pricing","price-list","csv"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer-Specific Pricing\n\nThe **Pricing** tab on a customer's detail page is where you record the negotiated prices that customer gets — overriding the standard catalog price. It appears for **Active** customers (Office Managers use it to adjust customer-specific pricing in context). Prospect and Archived customers do not show the Pricing tab.\n\n### Price Lists\n\nA customer can have one or more **price lists**. A price list is a named container with optional effective dating and a default flag.\n\n- Click **+ New List** to create one. The dialog captures **Name** (required), Description, an **Effective From** and **Effective To** date range, a **Default** toggle, and an **Active** toggle.\n- If a customer has more than one list, a **list selector** dropdown appears in the tab header so you can switch between them.\n- The header shows the selected list's name and its effective range (or 'Always' when both dates are blank).\n- Use the **edit** (pencil) icon to change list metadata, or the **delete** (trash) icon to remove it. Deleting a list that has entries warns you about how many entries will be removed.\n- When no list exists yet, an empty state offers **Create First List**.\n\n### Price List Entries (Quantity Breaks)\n\nEach price list holds **entries**. An entry ties a **part** to a **unit price** at or above a **minimum quantity** — this is how quantity-break (volume) pricing works: the entry whose minimum quantity is the highest value still ≤ the ordered quantity wins.\n\n- Click **+ Add** to open the entry dialog. Pick the **Part** (typeahead search; you can even create a new part inline), enter the **Unit Price** (required), the **Min Quantity** (required — the quantity threshold this price applies at), and the **Currency** (required). An optional **Notes** field captures context.\n- On an existing entry, the **Part** is locked — to re-price a different part, add a new entry.\n- **Inline cell editing:** in the entries table you can click directly on a **Min Quantity** or **Unit Price** cell to edit it in place. Press **Enter** to commit or **Escape** to cancel; a small spinner shows while saving and an error marker appears if the value is invalid. This is the fastest way to tweak a single number without opening the dialog.\n- Each row also has **edit** and **delete** icon buttons for full-dialog edits and removals.\n\n### Bulk Import from CSV\n\nWhen you have many entries to load, use **Import** (the upload-file button in the entries header):\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag a `.csv` onto the dropzone or click **Browse**. A **Download Template** link gives you the correct column layout.\n2. **Preview** — the system parses the file and shows a preview table with a summary of how many rows will be **added**, **updated**, or are in **error**. Each row is tagged with its action; error rows show the reason (e.g., unknown part number, bad price).\n3. **Apply** — the Apply button is disabled while any row is in error. Fix the file and re-upload, or proceed once it's clean. Use **Back** to return to the file picker.\n\nImported entries are matched to existing entries by part + minimum quantity, so re-importing an updated file updates the matching rows rather than duplicating them.\n\n### How Pricing Is Used Downstream\n\nThese negotiated prices feed the rest of quote-to-cash: when you add a line to a Sales Order (or Quote) for this customer and select a part, the line's unit price auto-fills from the customer's applicable price-list entry for the ordered quantity. That keeps negotiated pricing consistent without anyone re-typing it on every order.","sections":[]}"""
        });

