        // ── Customer Portal Access (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Portal Access",
            Slug = "customers-portal-access",
            Summary = "How to provision, enable, and disable external portal logins for customer contacts from the /customers/portal-access admin page.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 9,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers/portal-access"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","portal","access","contacts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer Portal Access\n\nThe **Portal Access** page (`/customers/portal-access`) is the cross-customer admin surface for granting your customers' contacts a login to the external customer portal. From one screen you can see who has access, provision new logins, and turn access on or off.\n\n### The Access Roster\n\nThe page is a single table listing every contact that has been provisioned, with columns:\n- **Contact Name** (Last, First format)\n- **Customer** — the company the contact belongs to\n- **Email** — the portal login identifier (the contact's email *is* their username)\n- **Last Login** — date/time of their last portal sign-in, or 'Never signed in' if they haven't yet\n- **Created** — when access was provisioned\n- **Enabled** — a toggle to turn the login on or off\n\nClick a row to jump to that customer's **Contacts** tab. The table is searchable and sortable like any other data table.\n\n### Provisioning Access for a Contact\n\nClick **Provision Portal Access** to open the provision dialog:\n\n1. The dialog loads the list of **eligible contacts** — these are contacts who have an **email address** (required, since email is the login identifier) and who do **not already** have a portal-access row.\n2. Pick a contact from the dropdown and confirm. The system creates the portal-access record (the operation is idempotent, so provisioning a contact that already has access is safe).\n3. If there are no eligible contacts, the dialog tells you so — this usually means every contact with an email already has access, or no contacts have an email on file yet. Add an email to the contact first (on the customer's Contacts tab), then provision.\n\n### Enabling and Disabling Access\n\nThe **Enabled** toggle on each row turns a contact's portal login on or off without deleting the record:\n- Flip it **off** to immediately revoke a contact's ability to sign in (e.g., they left the company) while keeping the audit trail and last-login history.\n- Flip it **on** to restore access.\n- The toggle disables briefly while the change is saving, and a confirmation snackbar names the affected contact.\n\n### Key Points\n\n- **Email is mandatory** — a contact with no email cannot be provisioned, because the portal uses email as the username.\n- **Provisioning is per-contact, not per-customer** — each individual person gets their own login. A single customer company can have several portal users.\n- **Disabling is reversible** — it preserves the record and history; you are not re-provisioning from scratch when you re-enable.\n- **The roster is cross-customer** — this page shows portal users across all customers in one place, which is why it lives under the Customers hub rather than on a single customer's detail page.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customers — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "customers-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and ancillary reference for Customers: accounting boundary, capability gating of tabs/credit card, Overview compliance/reference flags, recent-communications auto-logging, Segments/Import placeholders, completeness chip, and price-list effective dates.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Accounting-Boundary Behavior\n\nCustomer financial fields follow the ⚡ Accounting Boundary. When an external accounting provider (QuickBooks Online, etc.) is connected, the customer record syncs bidirectionally and the provider becomes the system of record for the financial side. The Overview tab then shows an accounting-integration badge plus the provider name, external ID, and reference. The app-owned, always-in-app data (addresses, contacts, interactions, price lists, sales orders, quotes) stays editable regardless of mode; only the accounting-bounded surfaces (invoices, payments, AR aging, credit terms) degrade to read-only or hidden when a provider is configured. In standalone mode (no provider) those surfaces are fully editable. The boundary is enforced through the capability mutex `CAP-ACCT-EXTERNAL ⊥ CAP-ACCT-BUILTIN`.\n\n## Capability Gating of Tabs and the Credit Card\n\nThe customer detail page is at `/customers/:id/:tab`. The middle tabs are individually capability-gated — when the backing capability is disabled the tab drops out of the layout entirely (the resolver filters it before render):\n\n- **Contacts** — `CAP-MD-CUSTOMER-CONTACTS`\n- **Addresses** — `CAP-MD-CUSTOMER-ADDRESSES`\n- **Interactions** — `CAP-MD-CUSTOMER-INTERACTIONS`\n\nOverview and Activity carry no per-tab capability and always render. The Customers module itself is gated by `CAP-MD-CUSTOMERS`; portal access by `CAP-EXT-CUSTOMER-PORTAL`. The **Credit Status card** on the Overview tab is wrapped in `*appCap=\"'CAP-O2C-CREDIT-LIMITS'\"` — COD / prepaid shops that don't extend credit can disable that capability and the card disappears, along with the Place Hold / credit-exposure surface. The same gate hides the credit fields in the customer detail dialog.\n\n## Overview Compliance and Reference Flags\n\nThe Overview tab carries a set of boolean compliance flags plus a customer-reference toggle, all persisted via `updateCustomer`:\n\n- **Compliance flags** — `isFdaRegulated`, `isAerospace`, `isAutomotive`, `isItarControlled`. Each is an independent toggle (label + help text from `customers.compliance.*`). A combined `hasComplianceFlag` indicator is true when any one is set; these flags feed segment filter expressions (e.g. `isAerospace = true`).\n- **Reference flags** — `isReferenceOk` marks the customer as approved to be used as a sales reference; `referenceNotes` holds free-text context. The notes field guards against silent loss: editing then navigating away without saving prompts a discard confirmation.\n\nToggles write optimistically through a `pendingFlags` set that clears on success or error.\n\n## Recent-Communications Auto-Logging\n\nThe Overview tab embeds the shared **Recent Communications** widget (`app-recent-communications`, entityType `Customer`). It reads the entity-activity feed and filters to communication-flavored verbs: `interaction-auto-received` / `interaction-auto-sent` (contact-anchored auto-log, written via the indexing-points pair so they surface on the customer), `communication-received` / `communication-sent`, and `interaction-logged` (manual Customer Interactions). The top 5 are shown; the full feed lives on the Activity tab. Because customers may use the manual Interactions feature, the empty state here is informational only (on leads it's a connect-a-mailbox CTA).\n\n## Segments and Import Placeholders\n\nTwo cross-customer hub sub-routes are **placeholder pages** (Phase 1r stubs; real CRUD ships later):\n\n- **`/customers/segments`** — renders representative example saved-segments (e.g. an aerospace high-value segment with filter summary `isAerospace = true AND openInvoiceTotal > $10K`) so admins can preview the feature before the segments table + filter-builder UI is built.\n- **`/customers/import`** — placeholder for the bulk-import wizard; the real upload + column-mapping flow lands in a follow-on.\n\nBoth are reachable today but do not yet persist anything. Literal sub-paths (`new`, `contacts`, `portal-access`, `segments`, `import`) are declared before the `:id` route so they don't resolve as customer IDs.\n\n## Completeness Chip\n\nThe customer list and detail header use the shared entity-completeness components against `entityType=\"Customer\"`:\n\n- **`app-entity-completeness-badge`** — compact inline indicator.\n- **`app-entity-completeness-chip`** — full chip; clicking opens a popover listing the per-capability gaps (which required fields/relationships are still missing). On the list grid the `completeness` column is hidden by default (`visible: false`, width 160px) and can be toggled on.\n\nCompleteness is computed server-side per entity, so the gaps reflect which optional-but-recommended data a customer record is still missing.\n\n## Price-List Effective Dates\n\nCustomer price lists (Pricing tab, `CAP-MD-CUSTOMERS` / Office Manager) carry an optional effective window: `effectiveFrom` and `effectiveTo` (ISO date strings, both nullable). The price-list form dialog enforces a cross-field validator — when both are set, `effectiveTo` must be strictly after `effectiveFrom`, otherwise the form raises an `effectiveRange` error. Blank dates mean \"Always\"; a single bound renders as \"From X\" or \"Until Y\" in the list header. This windowing lets a new contract-year price list be staged ahead of its start date without overwriting the current one.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Customers training modules");
    }
}
